  <brief_title>Vitamin D Treatment to Patients Suffering From Chronic Pain and Vitamin D Hypovitaminosis</brief_title>
  <official_title>A Randomised, Double-blind, Placebo-controlled Study to Check Whether Vitamin D Will Lead to a Decrease in Pain Intensity in Patients Suffering From Chronic Pain and Hypovitaminosis D</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Tel-Aviv Sourasky Medical Center</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Tel-Aviv Sourasky Medical Center</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The objective of this study is to check whether vitamin D will lead to a decrease in pain
      intensity compare to placebo, in patients suffering from chronic pain.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Vitamin D is a complex nutrient that functions as a hormone to benefit numerous body tissues.

      Vitamin D is naturally produced by skin exposed to ultraviolet B. Despite the fact that
      Israel is a sunny country, a majority of all patients, and particularly those with pain, have
      inadequate intake of vitamin D.

      Vitamin D therapy is easy for patients to self administer, well tolerated, and very
      economical.

      In this study, we'll check whether vitamin D will lead to a decrease in pain intensity in
      patients suffering from chronic low back pain.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
